{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17524360","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17524360"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T15:03:32+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T15:03:32+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13984"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13984","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13984"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.06,0.08,0.79,0.01,0.06]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6618"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"51188"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6618","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6618"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13984"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"36460"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"30"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1139"},{"type":"tags","id":"3465"},{"type":"tags","id":"4578"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4964"},{"type":"tags","id":"4977"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"9598"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11626"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"13409"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14133"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43926"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"51188","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/51188"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 63-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with a two-week history of a painful lump in his lower abdomen. He has a medical history of hypertension and type 2 diabetes mellitus. His regular medications include metformin and lisinopril. He does not smoke and drinks alcohol occasionally.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well. His pulse rate is 80/min, blood pressure 135/85 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 37.2\u00b0C. Abdominal examination reveals a tender, fluctuant mass in the left lower quadrant. The abscess is drained, but is observed to continue to bubble gas.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAs a result, a CT scan of the abdomen is performed, which shows a large collection of air in a confined space immediately under the anterior abdominal wall (image). The gas-filled cavity is intimately related to the sigmoid colon.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely underlying cause of this patient\u0027s condition?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Colorectal cancer","Crohn\u0027s disease","Diverticular disease","Appendicitis","Ulcerative colitis"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe clinical presentation and CT findings in this case are most consistent with an enterocutaneous fistula secondary to \u003Cstrong\u003Ediverticular disease\u003C/strong\u003E. The patient\u0027s age, the location of the fistula (related to the sigmoid colon), and the persistent gas bubbling from the drained abscess all point towards this diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDiverticular disease\u003C/strong\u003E is a common condition in older adults, particularly affecting the sigmoid colon. Complications of diverticulitis can include abscess formation and fistula development, as seen in this case. The intimate relationship between the gas-filled cavity and the sigmoid colon on CT imaging strongly supports this diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECrohn\u0027s disease\u003C/strong\u003E can also cause enterocutaneous fistulas, but it typically affects younger patients and is more commonly associated with the terminal ileum or right colon. The patient\u0027s age and the location of the fistula make this diagnosis less likely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAppendicitis\u003C/strong\u003E rarely causes enterocutaneous fistulas, and when it does, they are typically located in the right lower quadrant. The left-sided location and sigmoid involvement make appendicitis an unlikely cause in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EColorectal cancer\u003C/strong\u003E can occasionally lead to fistula formation, but this is a less common presentation. While it should be considered in the differential diagnosis, especially given the patient\u0027s age, diverticular disease remains a more likely explanation for the findings.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUlcerative colitis\u003C/strong\u003E primarily affects the mucosa of the colon and rectum, and rarely extends through the full thickness of the bowel wall. As a result, fistula formation is uncommon in ulcerative colitis, unlike in Crohn\u0027s disease. The lack of a history of chronic diarrhea or bloody stools, which are typical symptoms of ulcerative colitis, further makes this diagnosis unlikely in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn conclusion, diverticular disease is the most likely underlying cause of this patient\u0027s enterocutaneous fistula, given the clinical presentation, patient demographics, and CT findings. Further management would likely involve antibiotic therapy and surgical consultation for potential definitive treatment of the fistula.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Diverticular disease is a common cause of enterocutaneous fistulas in the sigmoid colon.","CT imaging is valuable in diagnosing and characterizing enterocutaneous fistulas.","Persistent gas bubbling from a drained abdominal wall abscess suggests an underlying enterocutaneous fistula."],"references":["Haack CI, Galloway JR, Srinivasan J. Enterocutaneous Fistulas: A Look at Causes and Management. Current Surgery Reports. 2014 Sep 16;2(10)."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"36460"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13984"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20878"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"20878","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/20878"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/CAFCJTQmwJiqmgBLHOvd8AdomKqf4P.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/CAFCJTQmwJiqmgBLHOvd8AdomKqf4P.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":1500,"height":1141}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"36460","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/36460"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-08-21T21:21:38+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-08-21T21:22:50+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6618"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"51188"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"5","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/5"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2d","name":"Gastroenterology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2a","name":"General Surgery","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links